sql:
SELECT single_family_limit
FROM housing_limits
WHERE year = 2022;

external_knowledge:
- The intention of the query seems to be to calculate the average number of accesses per user, not the average of the user_ids. It should be COUNT(al.access_id) instead of AVG(al.user_id); 
- 'Analyst' and 'government official' are roles of the users; 
- The time period is the year 2023.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) AS policy_change_count
FROM policy_changes
WHERE limit_id = 0 AND change_date LIKE '2023-%';

SELECT AVG(sales_volume) AS average_sales_volume
FROM market_trends
WHERE year = 2022 AND county_id = 0;

SELECT DISTINCT hl.limit_id
FROM housing_limits hl
JOIN access_logs al ON hl.limit_id = al.limit_id;

SELECT MIN(single_family_limit) AS min_single_family_limit
FROM housing_limits
WHERE year = 2023;
